This paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning, specifically investigating whether artificial neural networks encode grammatical distinctions necessary for inferring the idiosyncratic frame-selectional properties of verbs. The paper introduces five datasets and tests whether models can distinguish acceptable English verb-frame combinations from unacceptable ones using a sentence embedding alone. This suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing. Additionally, the paper involves the use of artificial neural networks, which suggests that it could also be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves the use of embeddings, which suggests that it could be categorized under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper involves the use of sentence embeddings, which suggests that it could also be categorized under cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition).
